00:41:36.410 --> 00:41:40.510
&gt;&gt; Hi, so what's your top
advice for aspiring authors?

00:41:40.510 --> 00:41:43.280
&gt;&gt; Alexandra Bracken: My
gosh, what's my top advice?

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:48.160
I mean, I feel like this is
advice you've probably heard

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:50.800
before but read everything.

00:41:50.800 --> 00:41:53.090
One of the really
fascinating things

00:41:53.090 --> 00:41:55.850
about reading different genres,
even genres you think you don't

00:41:55.850 --> 00:41:59.170
like is that they teach you
things that you might not expect

00:41:59.170 --> 00:42:01.720
or that you do expect
but in a very --

00:42:01.720 --> 00:42:08.090
gosh, I don't want to say
this -- in a very pointed way.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:11.260
Like for instance, when I
feel like I'm struggling

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:15.080
with plotting or figuring
out how to plant clues

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:17.010
about a mystery within
the story, I'll go back

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:20.180
and read thrillers and read
mysteries and you know,

00:42:20.180 --> 00:42:23.010
break down how they
pace out their reveals.

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:26.070
And reading romance
teaches you a great deal

00:42:26.070 --> 00:42:28.050
about creating a romantic arc.

00:42:28.050 --> 00:42:29.570
Can you figure out
what works for you

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:30.990
and what doesn't work for you?

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:34.390
Reading nonfiction is a
great source of inspiration

00:42:34.390 --> 00:42:37.030
and helps you develop your
own ideas about the world.

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:38.690
So read absolutely everything,

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:40.740
even if you don't think
you're going to like it.

00:42:40.740 --> 00:42:42.740
Keep reading everything.

00:42:42.740 --> 00:42:44.040
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Merry: We have time

00:42:44.040 --> 00:42:46.260
